    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I understand, let's keep it straightforward and academic. A prime number is a natural number greater than 1 that has no positive divisors other than 1 and itself. To determine if a number is prime, you can use the divisibility test, which involves checking if the number can be divided evenly by any other number besides 1 and itself.\n\nHere's a step-by-step method for testing if a number is prime:\n\n1. Write down the number you want to test.\n2. Start by dividing the number by the smallest prime number, which is 2.\n3. If the number is divisible by 2 (meaning there's no remainder), it's not a prime number.\n4. If the number isn't divisible by 2, move on to the next prime number, which is 3.\n5. Continue this process, dividing the number by each successive prime number (5, 7, 11, 13, etc.) until you either find a divisor or reach the square root of the number.\n6. If you find a divisor, the number is composite. If you reach the square root of the number without finding a divisor, the number is prime.\n\nFor example, let's test if 29 is a prime number:\n- It's not",
